  <img src="img/investors/david-gardner.jpg" alt="David Gardner">
</p>

<h4 class="margin-top">You’ve been called the “most active angel investor in NC”. How did you get into investing?</h4>

<p>
  6 years ago, David’s wife made him promise he would never start another company again. But for entrepreneurs, the itch for building companies never goes away.
</p>

<p>
  “In the beginning, I was just volunteering my time by advising and meeting with companies. There are not a lot of investors who are serial entrepreneurs themselves, so I felt like I had a lot to add to these teams and have a lot of insights that VCs do not have. The more pre-revenue companies I worked with, the more I saw a contrasting difference in teams that could execute what we were talking about and some that could not. I felt like I should be writing a few checks, and when they needed to raise money, I was in a position to know if they would use the funds wisely. My first dozen investments went really well and I had a 90% track record which is high for pre-revenue companies.”
</p>

<p>
  David actively angel invested for 5 years before starting <a href="http://cofounderscapital.com/">Cofounder’s Capital</a> last year.
</p>

<p class="margin-top center-align">
  <img src="img/articles/cofounders-capital-logo.png" alt="Cofounders Capital">
